agribusiness. Alternatively, professionals who are steeped in the culture of business emphasize the potential for market growth, for fostering better behemoths. Independent food store owners are then left to reconcile these ideas as they construct their professional identities and hone their business strategies. Drawing on extensive interviews and unique archival sources, Haedicke looks at how these groups make sense of their everyday work. He pays particular attention to instances in which individuals overcome the conflicting narratives of industry transformation and market expansion by creating new cultural concepts and organizational forms. At once an account of the sector's development and an analysis of individual choices within it, Organizing Organic provides a nuanced account of the way the organic movement continues to negotiate ethical values and economic productivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aFood industry and tradezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aIndustrial organizationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aNatural foods industryzUnited StatesxHistory. 4aactivism. 4acompromise. 4aconflict. 4aframing. 4ainstitutional logics. 4ainstitutional work. 4amarkets. 4aorganic foods. 4aorganic regulation. 4aorganization. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804798730zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804798730.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles